  </article>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a ball transfer table?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A ball transfer table is a flat surface embedded with omnidirectional ball casters that allow products to move in any horizontal direction with minimal push force. Each unit contains a large load ball on smaller support balls. Ball transfer tables are used at packing stations, conveyor intersections, and manual case handling areas in packaging lines.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How much weight can a ball transfer table hold?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Individual ball transfer units handle 15 to 2,000+ lbs depending on ball diameter and material. Table capacity equals the per-unit rating times the number of units under the smallest product. Standard 1-inch steel ball units rate 30-75 lbs each. Heavy-duty 2-inch units handle 200-600+ lbs each.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is the difference between fixed and spring-loaded ball transfers?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Fixed ball transfers stay at a set height , they do not retract. Spring-loaded units retract below the surface under load, allowing <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyors</a> to carry products over them. Pop-up (pneumatic) units extend on command for automated right-angle transfers.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What ball transfer spacing pattern should I use?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Use a staggered (diamond) pattern with 4-to-6-inch centers for most packaging applications. Staggered patterns ensure 3-4 balls always contact the product. Tighten to 3-inch spacing for small products. The minimum rule: at least three balls must support the product at all positions on the table.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
